2) The Plant Control System collects these data, making the information immediately available to the Plant staff, enabling them to assess and respond to the release from several locations within the Plant; 

3) An automatic chlorine shut-off system has been installed to minimize the volume of a chlorine release by securing the chlorine at the cylinders; 

4) The chlorine storage room was constructed as a ¿containment facility¿ to eliminate the free discharge of chlorine to the atmosphere. A critical component of this system is the ¿scrubber¿, which is capable, in the event of a release, of neutralizing 2000 pounds of chlorine. This ¿scrubber¿ is activated by data acquired by the leak sensors, and may be initiated manually by Plant staff; 

5) Several safe-work-practices for the operations and maintenance sections have been developed in conjunction with other safety programs to ensure employees work and respond safely.
The Alvarado Water Treatment Plant, in conjunction in with the Water Department Emergency Management Coordinator, have developed and tested a Chlorine Emergency Response Plan. The Emergency Response Plan was developed to support the Water Plant Operator in the event a chlorine release occurs and additional resources are needed to mitigate the situation. The San Diego Fire Department, Hazardous Materials Incident Response Team is dedicated to respond to our water plants if we have an incident. The Alvarado Water Treatment Plant has a Business Plan that identifies evacuation points on the site and provides additional emergency information about chlorine and additional contacts if needed. The Alvarado Water Treatment Plant has had no significant accidental releases of chlorine within the last five years requiring plant evacuation or requiring off site evacuation or consequences.

